Yes, you should combine all your bindings into a single `PYBIND11_MODULE` call. Having multiple `PYBIND11_MODULE` declarations with the same module name causes linking errors because each one creates a module initialization function with the same name (`PyInit_modulename`). Even using different module names would be impractical as you noted, since you'd need to import each one separately.

Here's how you can restructure your bindings:

1. Create a main binding file (e.g., `module_bindings.cpp`) that will contain the single `PYBIND11_MODULE` call:

```cpp:module_bindings.cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

// Forward declarations of binding functions
void bind_dummy_message(py::module& m);
void bind_other_message(py::module& m);
// ... other binding function declarations ...

PYBIND11_MODULE(protocol_name, m) {
    // Call individual binding functions
    bind_dummy_message(m);
    bind_other_message(m);
    // ... call other binding functions ...
}
```

2. Modify your auto-generated binding files to expose binding functions instead of using `PYBIND11_MODULE`:

```cpp:dummy_bind.cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include "dummy_message.h"

namespace py = pybind11;

void bind_dummy_message(py::module& m) {
    // Your existing binding code here
    py::class_<DummyMessage>(m, "DummyMessage")
        .def(py::init<>())
        // ... other bindings ...
        ;
}
```

This approach has several advantages:
- Avoids multiple definition errors
- Creates a single Python module that contains all your bindings
- Allows for better organization of binding code across multiple files
- Users only need to import one module to access all functionality

When compiling, make sure to compile all the binding files together into a single shared library. The module name in `PYBIND11_MODULE` will be the name users use to import your module in Python:

```python
import protocol_name
```

If you're using CMake, you'll want to compile all your binding source files into a single target:

```cmake
pybind11_add_module(protocol_name 
    module_bindings.cpp
    dummy_bind.cpp
    other_bind.cpp
    # ... other binding files ...
)
```

