print(minus(1, 2))  # This will compute 1 - (2 - 0.5)
```

The first approach (higher-order function) is more flexible because:
1. You can create different offset versions of the same function
2. You can keep the original function intact
3. You can change the offset amount dynamically

The second approach (decorator) is more elegant if you want to permanently modify the function and always use the same offset.

If you want to be able to toggle the offset behavior, you could create a more sophisticated version:

```python
def flexible_offset(n):
